  <!-- ═══ RISKS ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>

  <h3>Upside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Stronger AI edge adoption:</strong> As AI pushes to the edge, the need for advanced analog-to-digital converters and power management could accelerate faster than anticipated.</li>
    <li><strong>Capital returns:</strong> ADI consistently buys back stock and grows its dividend. Aggressive buybacks at undervalued levels would increase per-share intrinsic value.</li>
    <li><strong>Higher synergy capture:</strong> Further operational efficiencies post-Maxim acquisition could expand FCF margins structurally.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Semiconductor cycles:</strong> The analog IC market is cyclical. An extended industrial or automotive downturn could cause multiple years of negative FCF growth.</li>
    <li><strong>Intense competition:</strong> Competitors like Texas Instruments (TI) aggressively invest in internal manufacturing (e.g., 300mm wafer fabs), which could pressure ADI's pricing or market share.</li>
    <li><strong>Geopolitics:</strong> Disruptions in global supply chains or trade restrictions (especially concerning China) could materially impact revenue.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a 9% discount rate for ADI?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While technology companies often warrant higher discount rates (10%+), ADI operates in the more stable analog sector. Product lifecycles are long, customer bases are highly fragmented, and switching costs are significant. This predictability allows for a slightly lower required rate of return.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How does the Maxim Integrated acquisition affect this model?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The model uses TTM financials, which fully reflect the combined scale and initial cost synergies of the Maxim acquisition. The 8% growth rate assumes standard market growth without needing to factor in another transformational acquisition.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, and conviction in the assumptions.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

